# Geolocation "Near Me" Implementation

The requested feature enables users to sort the marketplace listings by nearest geographic proximity using their device's native GPS or IP geolocation.

## Changes Made

### 1. Database Indexing
- Updated [models/listing.js](file:///d:/PROJECTSDONE/HackAura/models/listing.js) to create a `2dsphere` index on the geographic `geometry` field. This allows MongoDB to properly calculate curvature and distances.

### 2. Backend Spatial Querying
- Updated the main [index](file:///d:/PROJECTSDONE/HackAura/controllers/listings.js#10-36) controller in [controllers/listings.js](file:///d:/PROJECTSDONE/HackAura/controllers/listings.js) to intercept explicit `lat` and `lng` query parameters.
- If geolocation coordinates are supplied, it dynamically applies the `$near` geospatial operator, fetching properties strictly up to 50km and natively sorting them from closest to furthest.

### 3. Frontend UI
- Injected a new `<button id="nearMeBtn">Near Me</button>` component directly beside the main marketplace `Hiring/Services/All` tabs in [views/listings/index.ejs](file:///d:/PROJECTSDONE/HackAura/views/listings/index.ejs).
- Bound the button to a native JavaScript `navigator.geolocation` method that prompts the user for position access.
- When granted, it reloads the same index page but passes `?lat=` and `?lng=` correctly down to the node backend.
- Handled visual toggles so the button is highlighted if geographical sorting is active, allowing users to clear it safely.
- Dynamically injected localized translated labels (`i18n`) without modifying the entire dictionary blob overhead.

## How to Verify Geographic Sorting
1. Navigate to the main `/home/listings` marketplace.
2. Click the new `Near Me` button.
3. Accept the browser's persistent location permission trigger if prompted.
4. Visually watch the button enter a loading state and reload the page.
5. Observe that listings are now displayed natively with the geographically closest at the topmost position.
